    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='# References to Starship, Terafab, and AI Compute Expansion Initiatives\n\nBelow is a comprehensive retrieval of all references found across the provided preamble excerpts, organized by topic.\n\n---\n\n## 1. STARSHIP\n\n### Financial & R&D Investment\n- The Space segment funded **$930 million** (Q1 2026) and **$3,004 million** (FY 2025) in R&D expense for the **next-generation Starship launch vehicle program**.\n- In 2025, the company **accelerated the Starship development timeline**, increasing Space segment R&D to **$3,004 million** from **$1,835 million** in 2024.\n- R&D costs from the Space segment increased by **$1,169 million** driven by **accelerated investment in the Starship vehicle**.\n- The Space segment generated a loss from operations of **$(657) million** and Segment Adjusted EBITDA of **$653 million** in 2025, including the impact of funding the Starship program.\n\n### Design & Capabilities\n- Starship is designed to enable a **step-function change** in launch capability across **reusability, payload capacity, and launch cadence**.\n- Starship is described as the **key enabler of the company\'s long-term growth strategy** by unlocking entirely new categories of missions.\n- Starship is the company\'s **next-generation vehicle** expected to dramatically expand launch capability through **full and rapid reusability** combined with unprecedented mass-to-orbit capability.\n- As the **most powerful launch system ever developed**, Starship V3 is expected to carry **100 metric tons** in a fully reusable configuration; future generations could reach **200 metric tons**, potentially as soon as Starship V4.\n- Starship is expected to be the **only vehicle with fully reusable first and second stages**, critical to reducing launch costs and increasing launch cadence.\n- The company believes Starship can eventually **reduce the cost to reach orbit by 99% or more** relative to the historical NASA average of **$18,500 per kilogram**.\n- Approximately **80% of Starship is manufactured in-house**, making it the world\'s most powerful and, eventually, most cost-effective launch vehicle.\n\n### Strategic Importance\n- Starship is **central to the goal of unlocking growth** through the company\'s unique vertically integrated business model.\n- Starship is the **only vehicle capable of deploying V3 satellites, V2 Mobile satellites, and orbital AI compute infrastructure** at scale; current Falcon 9 and Falcon Heavy rockets **cannot** perform these deployments.\n- Starship\'s lunar capabilities are expected to enable a **permanent presence on the Moon** for scientific and manufacturing pursuits, including factories that could manufacture **millions of AI compute satellites** deployed farther into space.\n- The company is collaborating with **NASA under the Artemis program** to land humans on the Moon using Starship—the first such mission since 1972.\n- The company has executed **11 Starship flight tests** and scheduled a **12th flight test** debuting the next-generation Starship vehicle and Super Heavy booster, powered by the next evolution of the Raptor engine, launching from a newly designed pad at Starbase.\n- **Payload delivery to orbit is expected to commence in the second half of 2026**.\n- Starship capacity of **100 metric tons** combined with a target of **thousands of launches per year** is the foundation for transporting approximately **one million metric tons to orbit annually**, powering **100 gigawatts of AI compute**.\n\n### Risk Factors\n- The development, testing, and deployment of Starship will require the investment of **significant additional capital resources**.\n- Starship development may face **similar or greater challenges** to past programs. Any significant delay in achieving key milestones, obtaining regulatory approvals, or increasing launch cadence would **impede expansion of service offerings, defer anticipated revenue streams, and negatively impact the growth trajectory and competitive positioning**.\n- If the company is unable to achieve commercial development, anticipated performance, launch cadence, or cost efficiencies within expected timelines, its ability to deploy next-generation satellites and orbital AI compute, reduce costs, realize projected revenue growth, and retain customers **could be materially and adversely affected**.\n\n---\n\n## 2. TERAFAB\n\n### Overview & Strategic Purpose\n- The company plans to **deepen its strategic collaboration with Tesla and Intel** through **Terafab**, an initiative to build the **world\'s largest chip manufacturing facility**.\n- A general framework has been agreed upon with Tesla for the future development of Terafab; specific projects will be subject to **separate negotiations and agreements** (including development timelines, milestones, and capital expenditures) and have **not yet been determined**.\n- The goal is to eventually achieve **one terawatt of annual compute production capacity**.\n- Terafab is intended to **expand internal chip manufacturing capabilities**, though the company expects to continue sourcing a **significant portion of compute hardware from third-party suppliers**.\n- Terafab is viewed as **complementary** to third-party relationships, augmenting access to compute hardware at massive scale and **further completing the highly vertically integrated compute platform** by extending control to the **foundational chip layer**.\n\n### Technical & Operational Details\n- Terafab will develop **end-to-end capabilities** spanning the design of lithography masks, fabrication of logic and memory chips, and advanced packaging—all in a **vertically integrated closed-loop single plant**.\n- This integration will enable **more rapid iteration** to improve chip design and performance.\n- The company plans to **design chips optimized for the space environment**.\n- **Intel** joined the Terafab project in **early April 2026**, contributing expertise in designing, fabricating, and packaging ultra-high-performance chips at scale.\n- Terafab leverages **shared engineering resources, intellectual property, and infrastructure across Tesla and SpaceX**, creating powerful ecosystem synergies that accelerate innovation cycles and reduce costs.\n- Significant **speed and cost advantages** from Terafab\'s vertical integration are expected, analogous to Starship\'s in-house manufacturing advantages.\n\n### Connection to AI Compute\n- Terafab directly enables **planned orders-of-magnitude increases in AI compute deployment in orbit**, which would be constrained by pure reliance on external foundries.\n- Terafab is expected to provide a **critical competitive advantage in the race to scale AI infrastructure**, especially as orbital AI compute satellite deployments begin.\n- The Terafab initiative is described as enabling the company to **alleviate potential future chip shortages**, **optimize compute performance**, and potentially **reduce overall compute costs**.\n- The company\'s "shovels-to-tokens" approach—extending verticalization from chips to data centers to model training—allows frontier models to be trained and iterated at **high velocity**, accelerating development cycles, eliminating external bottlenecks, and driving rapid, continuous improvements in model performance.\n\n### Risk Factors\n- The company\'s ability to **design, develop, and successfully commercialize Terafab** in rapidly evolving and competitive markets is listed as a key risk factor.\n\n---\n\n## 3. AI COMPUTE EXPANSION INITIATIVES\n\n### Capital Expenditure & Investment Scale\n- **AI capital expenditures for 2025** increased by **$7,094 million to $12,727 million** compared to **$5,633 million** in 2024 (which itself increased by **$5,170 million** from **$463 million** in 2023).\n- These increases were primarily driven by **significant investments in the rapid expansion of terrestrial data centers**, including development, construction, and equipping of new facilities and supporting infrastructure.\n- In the AI segment, 2025 R&D increased to **$5,064 million** from **$1,176 million** in 2024, driven by **accelerated deployment of compute for the development of Grok**.\n- AI segment R&D costs increased by **$3,888 million** driven by **depreciation of GPU hardware** and the **cost of cloud computing** as a result of data center expansions.\n- The company expects to **allocate substantial capital to expand compute infrastructure** and expects a **multi-year investment horizon** before AI Segment Adjusted EBITDA turns sustainably positive.\n- Capital expenditures will **scale as quickly as power and compute can be deployed** to address the **$26.5 trillion potential market opportunity for AI**.\n\n### COLOSSUS Facilities\n- **COLOSSUS** and **COLOSSUS II** collectively provide approximately **1.0 gigawatt of compute power**, with additional power capacity available for data center operations.\n- The company became the **first company to deploy a coherent gigawatt-scale AI training cluster**.\n- The first cluster of **COLOSSUS** was brought online in **122 days**, repurposing the shell of an existing factory.\n- The first cluster of **COLOSSUS II** was brought online even faster, in **91 days**.\n- For comparison, the industry benchmark to bring online a **100 megawatt greenfield data center is approximately two years**.\n- **COLOSSUS II** achieved data center construction costs that are **considerably lower than industry benchmarks on a per megawatt basis**.\n- COLOSSUS II became one of the **world\'s first data centers to deploy GB200s and GB300s** (the most advanced AI processors available at the time) at significant scale, and is currently powering training for next frontier models including **Grok-5**.\n- This dual speed and cost advantage stems from **complete vertical integration** and a shared culture across the Space, Connectivity, and AI segments.\n\n### Orbital AI Compute Vision\n- The company intends to **deploy the first modular orbital AI compute shells** and begin **monetizing capacity through the sale of AI software and AI compute** by the end of the decade.\n- The company aims to launch **100 gigawatts of AI compute capacity on solar-powered satellites each year**, equivalent to roughly **one-fifth of total annual U.S. power production in 2025**.\n- Orbital AI compute depends on three components: **payload** (Starship V3 at 100 metric tons), **satellite capacity** (early satellites generating **100 kilowatts** of compute power), and **launch frequency** (scaling to **thousands of launches per year**).\n- A deployment rate of approximately **10 gigawatts per year** would require a materially lower manufacturing and launch cadence but would still enable a **commercially attractive AI compute business with strong economic returns**.\n- The V3 satellite platform already incorporates **proprietary chips**, providing a foundation for AI-focused electronics in space.\n- Orbital AI compute is described as an **incredibly difficult challenge that only the company can solve at scale in the near term**.\n- Compute capacity in orbit will also advance the **human augmentation vision** by expanding the reach, speed, and capability of AI beyond what is possible with terrestrial compute.\n- The orbital AI compute goal is based on **reasoned engineering analyses** using currently available space-grade solar technology and does **not require fundamental technological advances** beyond existing capabilities.\n\n### AI Segment Financial Results\n- For Q1 2026, the AI segment generated revenue of **$818 million**, loss from operations of **$(2,469) million**, and Segment Adjusted EBITDA of **$(609) million**.\n- For FY 2025, the AI segment generated revenue of **$3,201 million** and a loss from operations.\n- AI segment revenue increased by **$581 million** as advertising, Grok and X subscriptions, and data licensing arrangements grew.\n- The AI segment was formed through the **acquisition of xAI in February 2026**.\n\n### Risk Factors\n- The company\'s ability to **scale and monetize AI products and services**, including the performance and adoption of frontier models and related applications, is a key risk.\n- Risks include the ability to **obtain sufficient power, GPUs, and other critical components** and manage the supply chain.\n- The company\'s initiatives to **develop orbital AI compute at scale** and **manufacture AI chips at scale** are in **early stages** and have not yet been proven at commercial scale, involving **significant technical complexity, unproven technologies, or technologies that do not exist**.\n- The company expects to incur **significant capital expenditures over a period of years** before AI products and services and other strategic initiatives reach the market.\n\n### Capital Allocation & Flexibility\n- Cash generated from core operations funds R&D projects including **Starship, next-generation satellites, construction of future data centers, and continued expansion of AI-enabled products**.\n- The company retains **flexibility to adjust spending across segments**; if near-term data center needs decrease or ramp more slowly, future AI capital expenditures may be **reduced and reallocated** to other segments.\n- The company may raise **additional capital or seek alternative financing** (including debt facilities, notes offerings, or bank borrowings) to fund rapid business growth.',
