    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='# Risk Factors & Forward-Looking Statements: Monetization Timing, Revenue Expectations, and Execution Timelines\n\n## 1. STARSHIP\n\n### Execution Timeline\n| Milestone | Status/Target |\n|-----------|--------------|\n| Flight tests completed | 11 to date; 12th scheduled (next-gen vehicle + Super Heavy booster) |\n| Payload delivery to orbit | **Second half of 2026** (following additional flight tests) |\n| Key milestones planned | Catching the upper stage; in-orbit propellant transfer demonstration |\n| Orbital AI compute satellites | **As early as 2028** |\n\n### Key Risk Factors\n- **Delays have occurred and will likely recur** due to: unforeseen technical challenges, supply chain disruptions, manufacturing difficulties, launch/fueling infrastructure delays (pads, air separation units, propellant production), mishaps, regulatory hurdles, and unanticipated redesigns.\n- Current rockets (**Falcon 9, Falcon Heavy**) are **not capable** of deploying V3 satellites, V2 Mobile satellites, or orbital AI compute infrastructure.\n- **Full reusability is critical**: "AI compute satellites at scale need full Starship reusability to be economically compelling." Without it, the company faces higher per-launch costs, slower deployment timelines, delayed revenue growth, and increased capital requirements.\n- **In-orbit refueling** is essential for lunar, Mars, and deep-space ambitions but has **never been demonstrated or attempted** and involves complex cryogenic propellant transfer in microgravity.\n- Regulatory delays (FAA launch/reentry licenses, spectrum authorizations, international approvals for constellations potentially numbering **up to one million satellites**) could materially disrupt operations.\n\n### Revenue/Growth Impact\n> "Any failure or delay in the development of Starship at scale or in achieving the required launch cadence, reusability and capabilities thereafter would delay or limit our ability to execute our growth strategy, including the deployment of next-generation satellites, global satellite-to-mobile connectivity, and orbital AI compute, which could materially adversely affect our business, financial condition, results of operations, and future prospects."\n\n> "Any significant delay... would impede the expansion of our service offerings, **defer anticipated revenue streams**, and negatively impact our growth trajectory and competitive positioning."\n\n---\n\n## 2. TERAFAB\n\n### Execution Timeline & Status\n| Aspect | Detail |\n|--------|--------|\n| Description | AI chip manufacturing initiative for vertical integration of advanced logic and memory chip design, fabrication, and deployment |\n| Partners | Framework agreement with **Tesla** and **Intel**, but neither is obligated to remain; definitive agreements may not be executed |\n| Current status | **Announced** — no committed operational date provided |\n\n### Key Risk Factors\n- "There can be **no assurance** that we will be able to achieve our objectives with respect to Terafab within the expected timeframes, or at all."\n- Terafab is intended to alleviate future AI chip shortages, particularly for orbital AI at scale, but the company **expects to continue sourcing a significant portion of compute hardware from third-party suppliers** indefinitely.\n- Collaboration expected with Tesla\'s "next-generation" processors as a "critical advantage."\n\n### Revenue/Growth Impact\n- No standalone revenue projections disclosed; Terafab is framed as a **cost-reduction and supply-chain resilience** initiative supporting AI compute and orbital infrastructure.\n- Falls under the broader risk: ability to "design, develop and successfully commercialize new and innovative technologies, products, and services, including our AI platforms and Terafab, and our ability to achieve and maintain a **low cost per token**."\n\n---\n\n## 3. AI COMPUTE\n\n### Execution Timeline\n| Milestone | Target |\n|-----------|--------|\n| Orbital AI compute satellite deployment | **As early as 2028** |\n| AI segment achieving sustained positive Adjusted EBITDA | **Multi-year investment horizon** — no date given; may never occur |\n| Monetization of existing AI user base | **Near-term focus** |\n| Orbital refueling (prerequisite for orbital AI at scale) | Undemonstrated; timeline unspecified |\n\n### Key Risk Factors\n- **"Multi-year investment horizon before these deployments translate into sustained positive AI Segment Adjusted EBITDA."**\n- The AI segment has **incurred significant operating losses since inception** and may not achieve or sustain profitability.\n- Viability of orbital AI compute depends on **solar energy cost advantages over terrestrial sources**; breakthroughs in terrestrial energy (e.g., nuclear) could **materially diminish** orbital AI viability.\n- A **material slowdown in AI application growth** or compute demand could mean existing terrestrial data centers sufficiently meet demand, reducing the need for orbital infrastructure.\n- Scaling laws (model performance improves with compute/data/model size) may not continue to hold indefinitely.\n- External compute monetization (e.g., cloud compute agreements with Anthropic) requires **substantial capital expenditures and management attention** and may create operational complexity around infrastructure allocation and prioritization.\n- Supply chain: dependency on third-party GPU suppliers who serve competitors and may prioritize other customers, increase prices, or delay deliveries.\n\n### Revenue/Growth Impact\n- AI segment is in **heavy investment mode**: Q1 2026 revenue of **$818M** vs. operating loss of **$(2,469M)** and Segment Adjusted EBITDA of **$(609M)**.\n- 2025 AI segment: revenue **$3,201M** with significant operating losses.\n- "Our AI segment may not achieve profitability."\n\n---\n\n## 4. CURRENT REVENUE-GENERATING PRODUCTS vs. FUTURE INITIATIVES\n\n### Currently Generating Revenue\n\n| Segment | 2025 Revenue | Q1 2026 Revenue | Profitability |\n|---------|-------------|----------------|---------------|\n| **Connectivity (Starlink)** | $11,387M | $3,257M | ✅ Profitable: 2025 EBITDA $7,168M; Q1 2026 EBITDA $2,087M |\n| **Space (Launch Services)** | $4,086M | (in Space segment total) | Marginally: 2025 EBITDA $653M |\n| **AI (Grok, X monetization, advertising)** | $3,201M | $818M | ❌ Losses: 2025 and Q1 2026 operating losses in the billions |\n\n**Connectivity** is the primary current profit driver, with 2025 revenue growth of **49.8%** YoY.\n\n**AI revenue sources currently include**:\n- High-impact advertising inventory on X\n- Grok Business and Grok Enterprise (license-, consumption-, or outcome-based pricing)\n- Cloud compute services agreements (e.g., with Anthropic for unused compute capacity)\n- Software development partnerships (e.g., Cursor)\n\n### Future Initiatives (No Current Revenue)\n\n| Initiative | Prerequisites | Monetization Risk |\n|-----------|---------------|-------------------|\n| **Next-gen V3 Starlink satellites** | Starship operational at scale | Cannot deploy on Falcon 9/Heavy |\n| **V2 Satellite-to-mobile connectivity** | Starship, spectrum approvals | Regulatory uncertainty |\n| **Orbital AI compute** | Starship reusability, in-orbit refueling, regulatory approvals, Terafab | Viability contingent on energy economics; demand uncertainty |\n| **Lunar economy** | Starship, in-orbit refueling (undemonstrated) | "Never been" navigated or monetized |\n| **Interplanetary missions** | All of the above | Longest time horizon, highest uncertainty |\n| **Terafab (chip manufacturing)** | Tesla/Intel partnership execution | No assurance of timeline or completion |\n\n### Forward-Looking Statement Caution\n> "Forecasts, goals, milestones, and expectations that cover **multi-year time horizons, or unknown timelines**, inherently involve increased risks with respect to predictability and actual results may differ materially from current expectations."\n\n> "We may elect to allocate capital and resources to long-term initiatives even if alternative uses with more short-term upside are available."\n\n> "Many of the products and services that are [future-oriented]... are subject to significant technical complexity, capital requirements, new innovations and regulatory approvals."\n\n---\n\n## Summary of Key Timing Dependencies\n\n```\nTerafab (chip supply)\n    ↓\nStarship (2026 payload delivery → full reusability → rapid cadence)\n    ↓\nIn-orbit refueling (undemonstrated)\n    ↓\nOrbital AI Compute (~2028 earliest) ← depends on energy economics & AI demand\n    ↓\nLunar Economy / Mars (longest horizon)\n```\n\nEach downstream initiative inherits the execution risk of every upstream dependency, with **no binding timelines** beyond the 2026 Starship payload delivery target and the 2028 orbital AI compute aspiration.',
