        output="Based on the provided Management’s Discussion and Analysis (MD&A) and related sections, here is the segment revenue breakdown, Adjusted EBITDA figures, and capital expenditure details for SpaceX's Space, Connectivity, and AI segments.\n\n### **Segment Revenue Breakdown**\nThe revenue for each segment is detailed in the financial tables:\n\n| Segment | Q1 2026 | Q1 2025 | Full Year 2025 | Full Year 2024 | Full Year 2023 |\n| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |\n| **Space** | $619 million | $865 million | $4,086 million | $3,796 million | $3,557 million |\n| **Connectivity** | $3,257 million | $2,475 million | $11,387 million | $7,599 million | $3,869 million |\n| **AI** | $818 million | $727 million | $3,201 million | $2,620 million | $2,961 million |\n| **Total** | $4,694 million | $4,067 million | $18,674 million | $14,015 million | $10,387 million |\n\n**Key Insight:** The Connectivity segment, driven by Starlink, is the largest revenue contributor, showing strong growth. The AI segment's revenue is growing but is currently the smallest of the three.\n\n---\n\n### **Segment Adjusted EBITDA**\nSegment Adjusted EBITDA is a non-GAAP measure reconciled from segment income (loss) from operations.\n\n| Segment | Q1 2026 | Q1 2025 | Full Year 2025 | Full Year 2024 | Full Year 2023 |\n| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |\n| **Space** | $(351) million | $224 million | $653 million | $1,154 million | $997 million |\n| **Connectivity** | $2,087 million | $1,618 million | $7,168 million | $3,849 million | $1,602 million |\n| **AI** | $(609) million | $(112) million | $(1,237) million | $347 million | $1,222 million |\n| **Total** | $1,127 million | $1,730 million | $6,584 million | $5,350 million | $3,821 million |\n\n**Key Insight:** Connectivity is the only consistently profitable segment on an Adjusted EBITDA basis. The AI segment is currently in a significant investment phase, generating substantial losses, while Space's profitability has declined as it funds Starship development.\n\n---\n\n### **Capital Expenditures (CapEx) by Segment**\nCapital expenditures are detailed in a table within the MD&A:\n\n| Segment | Q1 2026 | Q1 2025 | Full Year 2025 | Full Year 2024 | Full Year 2023 |\n| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |\n| **Space** | $1,052 million | $759 million | $3,832 million | $2,032 million | $1,497 million |\n| **Connectivity** | $1,332 million | $814 million | $4,178 million | $3,498 million | $2,455 million |\n| **AI** | $7,723 million | $2,567 million | $12,727 million | $5,633 million | $463 million |\n| **Total** | $10,107 million | $4,140 million | $20,737 million | $11,163 million | $4,415 million |\n\n**Key Insight:** Capital spending is heavily concentrated in the AI segment (77% of total CapEx in Q1 2026), reflecting massive investments in compute infrastructure. The Space segment's CapEx is increasing, driven by Starship launch site infrastructure investments.\n\n### **Summary**\n*   **Revenue:** Connectivity is the dominant segment, with AI showing rapid growth.\n*   **Profitability (Adj. EBITDA):** Connectivity is the profit engine. Space is marginally profitable but investing heavily in R&D. AI is in a steep loss-making phase due to strategic investments.\n*   **Capital Allocation:** The vast majority of capital is being deployed into the AI segment to build out compute infrastructure, with significant ongoing investment in Space for Starship.",
